{{left communism sidebar|expanded=all}}
'''General Workers' Union of Germany''' ({{lang-de|Allgemeine Arbeiter-Union Deutschlands}}; AAUD), was the name of factory organisations formed following the [[German Revolution of 1918–1919]] in opposition to the traditional trade unions. The AAUD was formed by the [[left communist]]s in the [[Communist Workers' Party of Germany]] (KAPD) who considered [[trade union|organising]] based on [[craft|trade]]s as being an outmoded form of organisation and instead advocated organising workers based on factories, thus forming the AAUD. They were influenced by the [[industrial unionism]] of the [[Industrial Workers of the World]].<ref name="Trend">{{cite web|title=Vor 80 Jahren|url=http://www.trend.infopartisan.net/trd0999/t400999.html|website=Trend|publisher=Redaktion trend bzw. "Arbeitskreis Kapitalismus aufheben"|accessdate=29 August 2016}}</ref> The council communists organised these factory organisations as the basis for region-wide [[workers' councils]].<ref>[http://www.marxists.org/archive/reichenbach/1969/retrospect.htm Bernhard Reichenbach, ''The KAPD in Retrospect: An Interview with a Member of the Communist Workers Party of Germany'']</ref>
A section of the AAUD led by [[Otto Rühle]], based in [[Essen]], split from the AAUD, forming the Essen tendency of the AAUD, [[Allgemeine Arbeiter-Union – Einheitsorganisation]].<ref>[http://libcom.org/files/dutchleft.pdf The German-Dutch Communist Left - Philippe Bourrinet]</ref>
