The '''Loma people''', sometimes called '''Loghoma''', '''Looma''', '''Lorma''' or '''Toma''', are a West African [[ethnic group]] living primarily in the northern mountainous, sparsely populated regions of [[Guinea]] and [[Liberia]].<ref name="loma">{{Cite thesis | url=http://anthropology.si.edu/leopold/pubs/leopold_1991_chapter2.htm | last=Leopold | first=Robert Selig | title=Prescriptive Alliance and Ritual Collaboration in Loma Society | year=1991 | chapter=2 | publisher=Indiana University | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716235904/http://anthropology.si.edu/leopold/pubs/leopold_1991_chapter2.htm | archivedate=2011-07-16 | df= }}</ref><ref name="AppiahGates2010p84">{{cite book|author1=Anthony Appiah|author2=Henry Louis Gates|title=Encyclopedia of Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A0XNvklcqbwC&pg=RA1-PA643|year=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-533770-9|page=84}}</ref> Their population was estimated at 330,000 in the two countries in 2010.<ref name="Sherman2010p211">{{cite book|author=Frank Sherman|title=Liberia: The Land, Its People, History and Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1lstRzSWEcUC&pg=PA211|year=2010|publisher=New Africa Press|isbn=978-9987-16-025-9|pages=211–212}}</ref> They are closely related to the [[Mende people]].<ref name="AppiahGates2010p84"/>

The Loma speak [[Loma language|a language]] in the Southwestern branch of the [[Mande languages]], belonging to the Niger-Congo family of languages. The language is similar to the [[Kpelle language|Kpelle]], [[Mende language|Mende]], [[Gola people|Gola]], [[Vai people|Vai]], and [[Gbandi|Bandi]] languages.<ref name="loma"/> The Loma refer to their language as [[Loma language|Löömàgòòi]] {{IPA-xx|lɔːmàɡòːi|}} or Löghömàgòòi {{IPA-xx|lɔɣɔmàɡòːi|}}).<ref name="loma"/> The Loma people, led by Wido Zobo and assisted by a Loma weaver named Moriba, developed a writing script for their language in the 1930s.<ref name="Sherman2010p211"/> This writing script contains at least 185 characters.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Anthony Appiah|author2=Henry Louis Gates|title=Encyclopedia of Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A0XNvklcqbwC&pg=RA1-PA643|year=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-533770-9|page=552}}</ref>

The [[Malinke]], [[Konyaka]], and [[Kissi people|Kissi]] refer to the Loma as ''Toma''.<ref name="ethnologue_toma"/><ref name ="loma"/> Loma refer to themselves as Löömàgìtì ({{IPA-xx|lɔːmàɡìtì}}, or Löghömagiti {{IPA-xx|lɔɣɔmaɡiti|}} in Guinea).<ref name="loma"/> They have retained their Traditional Religion, and resisted the Islamic jihads. The Loma people called the religious conflict with [[Mandinka people]] as a historic 'rolling war'.<ref>Christian K. Højbjerg (2010), Victims And Heroes: Manding Historical Imagination In A Conflict-Ridden Border Region (Liberia-Guinea), in ''The Powerful Presence of the Past'', Brill Academic, {{ISBN|978-9004191402}}, pages 273-294</ref>

The Loma people are notable for their large wooden masks that merge syncretic animal and human motifs. These masks have been a part of their ''Poro'' secret rites of passage. The largest masks are about six feet high, contain feather decorations and believed by Loma to have forest spirits.<ref name="Olukoju2006">{{cite book|author=Ayodeji Olukoju|title=Culture and Customs of Liberia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jOo6fCPSt0QC&pg=PA61| year=2006|publisher= Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-33291-3|pages=61–62}}</ref>

The Loma people farm rice, but in shifting farms. They are exogamous people, with patrilineal social organization in matters related to inheritance, succession and lineage affiliations with one-marriage rule. Joint families, or virilocal communities are common, wherein families of brothers settle close to each other.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Currens | first=Gerald E. | title=The Loma Avunculate: An Exercise in the Utility of Two Models | journal=Ethnology | publisher=University of Pittsburgh Press | volume=11 | issue=2 | year=1972 | page=111 | doi=10.2307/3773294 }}</ref>

