The '''Wochua''' (singular '''Achua''') was the [[endonym]] of a [[pygmy]] people<ref name=EB1911>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Wochua |volume=28 |page=767}}</ref> of the forests of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], south of the [[Welle River]]. They were first described in the Western world in 1880–1883 by Wilhelm Junker.<ref name=EB1911/> They may be the same as the [[Kango people|Kango]] [[Mbuti]], who are called ''Batchua'' (the root is ''[[Abatwa|Twa]]'', pronounced ''Cwa'' {{IPA-xx|tʃwa|}} in Congo); they are reported to have associated with the [[Mayogo language|Maigo]] (patrons of the Kango), the [[Mamvu language|Momfu]] (patrons of the Efé, but ''Wochua'' is a Bantu term), and the Mabode (unidentified).

